{
  "Which of the following is a strong acid that completely dissociates in water?": "",
  "HF": "",
  "CH₃COOH": "",
  "HCl": "",
  "H₂CO₃": "",
  "HCl (hydrochloric acid) is one of the six strong acids that completely dissociate in water. CH₃COOH, HF, and H₂CO₃ are all weak acids that only partially dissociate.": "",
  "What is the pH of a 0.001 M HCl solution?": "",
  "1": "",
  "3": "",
  "7": "",
  "11": "",
  "HCl completely dissociates, so [H⁺] = 0.001 M = 10⁻³ M. pH = -log[H⁺] = -log(10⁻³) = 3.": "",
  "In the Bronsted-Lowry definition, a base is:": "",
  "A substance that produces OH⁻ in water": "",
  "A proton (H⁺) donor": "",
  "An electron pair donor": "",
  "A proton (H⁺) acceptor": "",
  "In the Bronsted-Lowry definition, a base accepts a proton (H⁺). This is broader than the Arrhenius definition, which requires producing OH⁻ in water.": "",
  "What is the conjugate base of H₂SO₄?": "",
  "HSO₄⁻": "",
  "H₂O": "",
  "SO₄²⁻": "",
  "H₃SO₄⁺": "",
  "A conjugate base is formed when an acid donates one proton. H₂SO₄ loses one H⁺ to form HSO₄⁻ (hydrogen sulfate ion), which is its conjugate base.": "",
  "If a solution has a pOH of 3, what is its pH at 25°C?": "",
  "4": "",
  "At 25°C, pH + pOH = 14. Therefore, pH = 14 - 3 = 11. This solution is basic because its pH is above 7.": "",
  "Which of the following is the weakest acid?": "",
  "HCN (Ka = 6.2 × 10⁻¹⁰)": "",
  "HCl (Ka very large)": "",
  "CH₃COOH (Ka = 1.8 × 10⁻⁵)": "",
  "HF (Ka = 6.6 × 10⁻⁴)": "",
  "The smaller the Ka, the weaker the acid. HCN has the smallest Ka (6.2 × 10⁻¹⁰), meaning it dissociates the least and is the weakest acid listed.": "",
  "What is the relationship between Ka and Kb for a conjugate acid-base pair at 25°C?": "",
  "Ka / Kb = 1": "",
  "Ka + Kb = 14": "",
  "Ka = Kb for all conjugate pairs": "",
  "Ka × Kb = Kw = 1.0 × 10⁻¹⁴": "",
  "For any conjugate acid-base pair at 25°C, Ka × Kb = Kw = 1.0 × 10⁻¹⁴. A strong acid has a weak conjugate base (large Ka × small Kb = Kw).": "",
  "Which species acts as an amphoteric substance?": "",
  "NaOH": "",
  "NaCl": "",
  "Water is amphoteric (amphiprotic) because it can act as both an acid (donating H⁺) and a base (accepting H⁺). Its autoionization: 2H₂O ⇌ H₃O⁺ + OH⁻ demonstrates both roles.": "",
  "A 0.10 M solution of a weak acid HA has a pH of 3.0. What is the Ka of this acid?": "",
  "1.0 × 10⁻⁵": "",
  "1.0 × 10⁻²": "",
  "1.0 × 10⁻³": "",
  "1.0 × 10⁻⁷": "",
  "[H⁺] = 10⁻³ M. Ka = [H⁺][A⁻]/[HA] = (10⁻³)(10⁻³)/(0.10 - 10⁻³) ≈ 10⁻⁶/0.099 ≈ 1.0 × 10⁻⁵.": "",
  "What is the pH of pure water at 25°C?": "",
  "0": "",
  "14": "",
  "Pure water autoionizes: [H⁺] = [OH⁻] = 1.0 × 10⁻⁷ M at 25°C. pH = -log(1.0 × 10⁻⁷) = 7.0, which is neutral.": "",
  "What is an 'Arrhenius acid'?": "",
  "Any substance that donates a proton": "",
  "A substance that produces hydrogen ions (H⁺) when dissolved in water": "",
  "Any substance with a pH less than 7": "",
  "An electron pair acceptor": "",
  "An Arrhenius acid produces H⁺ (or H₃O⁺) ions when dissolved in water. This is the narrowest definition of an acid, limited to aqueous solutions.": "",
  "What does 'Bronsted-Lowry acid' mean?": "",
  "A proton (H⁺) donor in any solvent or reaction": "",
  "A substance that produces H⁺ ions in water": "",
  "A substance that tastes sour": "",
  "A Bronsted-Lowry acid is a proton donor. This definition is broader than Arrhenius because it applies to any reaction, not just aqueous solutions.": "",
  "What is a 'Lewis acid'?": "",
  "A proton donor": "",
  "Any substance with a high Ka value": "",
  "A Lewis acid accepts an electron pair. This is the broadest definition of acidity. Examples include BF₃, AlCl₃, and metal cations like Fe³⁺, which accept electron pairs from Lewis bases.": "",
  "What does 'conjugate acid-base pair' mean?": "",
  "An acid and base with the same Ka value": "",
  "Two species that differ by exactly one proton (H⁺), where the acid has the extra proton": "",
  "Any acid and base mixed together": "",
  "Two substances that always neutralize each other": "",
  "A conjugate acid-base pair consists of two species that differ by one proton. When an acid donates H⁺, it becomes its conjugate base. When a base accepts H⁺, it becomes its conjugate acid.": "",
  "What is 'Ka' (acid dissociation constant)?": "",
  "The equilibrium constant for the dissociation of a weak acid in water, measuring acid strength": "",
  "The pH of a 1 M acid solution": "",
  "The concentration of H⁺ ions in a solution": "",
  "The rate at which an acid dissociates": "",
  "Ka is the equilibrium constant for the reaction HA ⇌ H⁺ + A⁻. A larger Ka indicates a stronger acid (more dissociation). For acetic acid, Ka = 1.8 × 10⁻⁵.": "",
  "What does 'autoionization of water' refer to?": "",
  "The dissolution of salts in water": "",
  "The process where water molecules transfer protons among themselves: 2H₂O ⇌ H₃O⁺ + OH⁻, with Kw = 1.0 × 10⁻¹⁴ at 25°C": "",
  "The decomposition of water into hydrogen and oxygen gas": "",
  "The evaporation of water at the surface": "",
  "Water undergoes autoionization where one molecule donates H⁺ to another: 2H₂O ⇌ H₃O⁺ + OH⁻. The equilibrium constant Kw = [H₃O⁺][OH⁻] = 1.0 × 10⁻¹⁴ at 25°C.": "",
  "What is 'pH'?": "",
  "A measure of how fast an acid reacts": "",
  "The ratio of acid to base in a solution": "",
  "The negative base-10 logarithm of the hydrogen ion concentration: pH = -log[H⁺]": "",
  "The concentration of hydroxide ions in a solution": "",
  "pH = -log[H⁺] provides a convenient scale for expressing acidity. pH < 7 is acidic, pH = 7 is neutral, and pH > 7 is basic (at 25°C).": "",
  "What does 'amphoteric' mean?": "",
  "A substance that can act as either an acid or a base depending on the reaction conditions": "",
  "A substance that catalyzes acid-base reactions": "",
  "A substance that only acts as an acid": "",
  "A substance that is neither acidic nor basic": "",
  "An amphoteric substance can behave as either an acid or a base. Water is the classic example: it donates H⁺ to strong bases and accepts H⁺ from strong acids.": "",
  "What is the 'leveling effect'?": "",
  "All acids have the same strength in water, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Adding a base levels the pH to 7 because conventional analysis of effect suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "In water, all strong acids are leveled to the same strength (H₃O⁺) because water cannot differentiate between acids stronger than H₃O⁺": "",
  "Dilution makes all acids equally weak in most scenarios involving effect factors": "",
  "The leveling effect means that in water, all strong acids (HCl, HBr, HI, etc.) appear equally strong because they all donate their proton completely to water, forming H₃O⁺. To distinguish their strengths, a weaker base solvent is needed.": "",
  "What does 'percent ionization' mean?": "",
  "The fraction of weak acid molecules that dissociate, expressed as ([H⁺]/initial [HA]) × 100%": "",
  "The percentage of water molecules that ionize": "",
  "The percentage of strong acid in a mixture": "",
  "The ratio of Ka to Kb": "",
  "Percent ionization = ([H⁺] at equilibrium / initial [HA]) × 100%. It increases as the acid is diluted and is always 100% for strong acids.": "",
  "A farmer tests her soil and finds it has a pH of 4.5, which is too acidic for growing tomatoes (optimal pH 6.0-6.8). She plans to add calcium carbonate (lime) to raise the pH. What acid-base reaction occurs when lime is added to acidic soil?": "",
  "CaCO₃ is an acid that reacts with the basic components of soil": "",
  "CaCO₃ acts as a base, neutralizing H⁺ ions in the soil: CaCO₃ + 2H⁺ → Ca²⁺ + H₂O + CO₂": "",
  "CaCO₃ decomposes into Ca and CO₃, releasing heat that evaporates the acid": "",
  "CaCO₃ adds more H⁺ ions to dilute the acid": "",
  "Calcium carbonate is a base (the carbonate ion accepts protons). It reacts with H⁺ ions in the acidic soil, consuming them and producing water and CO₂, thereby raising the pH.": "",
  "A swimming pool manager notices the pH has dropped to 6.8 after a rainstorm. She adds sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO₃) to raise it. NaHCO₃ is amphoteric but acts primarily as a base in this situation. What reaction raises the pool's pH?": "",
  "HCO₃⁻ + H⁺ → H₂CO₃ → H₂O + CO₂, consuming excess H⁺ and raising pH": "",
  "NaHCO₃ → Na⁺ + H⁺ + CO₃²⁻, adding more H⁺": "",
  "NaHCO₃ reacts with chlorine to form a basic compound": "",
  "NaHCO₃ evaporates excess water, concentrating OH⁻ ions": "",
  "The bicarbonate ion acts as a Bronsted-Lowry base, accepting H⁺ from the acidic water: HCO₃⁻ + H⁺ → H₂CO₃ (which decomposes to H₂O + CO₂). This removes excess H⁺, raising the pH.": "",
  "A medical student learns that blood pH must be maintained between 7.35 and 7.45. If blood pH drops below 7.35 (acidosis), the body responds by increasing breathing rate. How does faster breathing help correct acidosis?": "",
  "Faster breathing cools the body, slowing acid production": "",
  "Faster breathing adds more N₂, which dilutes the acid in the blood": "",
  "Faster breathing brings in more oxygen, which is basic": "",
  "Faster breathing expels more CO₂, shifting the equilibrium CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H₂CO₃ ⇌ H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ to the left, reducing [H⁺] and raising pH": "",
  "Increased breathing removes CO₂ from the blood. By Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ shifts left, consuming H⁺ and raising blood pH back toward normal.": "",
  "An industrial chemist works with concentrated sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄). She knows it is a diprotic acid with a strong first dissociation and a weak second dissociation (Ka2 = 0.012). If she dissolves H₂SO₄ in water to make a 1.0 M solution, what is the approximate [H⁺]?": "",
  "Slightly greater than 1.0 M": "",
  "0.50 M, even when": "",
  "1.0 M, as conventional": "",
  "2.0 M, despite what": "",
  "The first dissociation is complete (Ka1 is very large), giving 1.0 M H⁺ and 1.0 M HSO₄⁻. The second dissociation (Ka2 = 0.012) is weak, contributing a small additional amount of H⁺. Total [H⁺] is slightly above 1.0 M.": "",
  "A food scientist measures the pH of lemon juice as 2.0 and orange juice as 3.5. A customer says the lemon juice is 'a little more acidic' than orange juice. By how many times is the [H⁺] in lemon juice greater than in orange juice?": "",
  "1.5 times greater": "",
  "150 times greater": "",
  "About 32 times greater": "",
  "15 times greater": "",
  "pH is logarithmic. Difference = 3.5 - 2.0 = 1.5 pH units. [H⁺] ratio = 10^1.5 = 31.6 ≈ 32 times. Lemon juice is about 32 times more acidic than orange juice, not just 'a little more.'": "",
  "A dentist explains to a patient that tooth enamel (hydroxyapatite) dissolves in acid: Ca₅(PO₄)₃OH + H⁺ → Ca²⁺ + HPO₄²⁻ + H₂O. Fluoride treatments convert some hydroxyapatite to fluorapatite (Ca₅(PO₄)₃F). Why is fluorapatite more resistant to acid?": "",
  "Fluorapatite has a lower Ksp than hydroxyapatite, making it less soluble in acid; F⁻ is a weaker base than OH⁻ and does not react as readily with H⁺": "",
  "Fluorine is a stronger base than hydroxide and neutralizes more acid": "",
  "Fluoride kills the bacteria that produce acid": "",
  "Fluorine atoms form a physical barrier over the tooth surface": "",
  "Fluorapatite is thermodynamically more stable (lower Ksp) than hydroxyapatite. The fluoride ion is a weaker base than hydroxide, so it is less likely to react with H⁺ from acids, making fluorapatite more acid-resistant.": "",
  "A cleaning product label warns not to mix bleach (NaClO, basic) with toilet bowl cleaner (HCl, acidic). A student wonders what dangerous product forms. The reaction is: NaClO + 2HCl → Cl₂ + NaCl + H₂O. Identify the acid-base interaction that initiates this reaction.": "",
  "HCl acts as an acid, donating protons that react with the basic hypochlorite ion, ultimately producing toxic Cl₂ gas": "",
  "The two substances combine to form a neutral salt only": "",
  "NaCl acts as a catalyst for the production of Cl₂": "",
  "NaClO acts as an acid, donating a proton to HCl": "",
  "HCl is a strong acid that protonates the hypochlorite ion (ClO⁻, a weak base). The resulting HOCl reacts with more HCl to produce toxic Cl₂ gas. This is why mixing bleach and acid cleaners is extremely dangerous.": "",
  "A marine biologist studies ocean acidification. As atmospheric CO₂ increases, more dissolves in seawater: CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻. Ocean pH has dropped from 8.2 to 8.1 over the past century. What percentage increase in [H⁺] does this represent?": "",
  "About 26%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 1%": "",
  "[H⁺] at pH 8.2 = 6.31 × 10⁻⁹ M. [H⁺] at pH 8.1 = 7.94 × 10⁻⁹ M. Increase = (7.94-6.31)/6.31 × 100% ≈ 26%. A 0.1 pH drop represents a 26% increase in acidity.": "",
  "An antacid tablet contains 500 mg of CaCO₃. A patient with acid reflux has excess stomach acid (approximately 0.10 M HCl). The reaction is CaCO₃ + 2HCl → CaCl₂ + H₂O + CO₂. How many mL of 0.10 M HCl can one tablet neutralize? (Molar mass CaCO₃ = 100.09 g/mol)": "",
  "200 mL": "",
  "100 mL": "",
  "50 mL": "",
  "500 mL": "",
  "Moles CaCO₃ = 0.500/100.09 = 0.00500 mol. Each mole neutralizes 2 mol HCl: 0.00500 × 2 = 0.0100 mol HCl. Volume = 0.0100/0.10 = 0.100 L = 100 mL.": "",
  "A wine maker monitors the acidity of her wine using tartaric acid (H₂C₄H₄O₆, a weak diprotic acid). She measures the pH at 3.2. She wants to reduce the acidity (raise pH) by adding potassium bicarbonate (KHCO₃). What type of reaction occurs between the tartaric acid and KHCO₃?": "",
  "An acid-base neutralization where the bicarbonate ion (base) accepts a proton from tartaric acid, producing CO₂ gas and water": "",
  "A decomposition reaction where tartaric acid breaks down": "",
  "An oxidation-reduction reaction": "",
  "A precipitation reaction forming an insoluble salt": "",
  "KHCO₃ provides the bicarbonate ion, which acts as a Bronsted-Lowry base. It accepts H⁺ from the tartaric acid: H₂C₄H₄O₆ + HCO₃⁻ → HC₄H₄O₆⁻ + H₂O + CO₂. The CO₂ bubbles off, driving the reaction.": ""
}